pparatuses as part of the new conditions of globalization and transnational capital accumulation. Building upon themes of state restructuring found in Poulantzas and Miliband, Barrow establishes the outlines of an approach that integrates the thought of both to propose a synthetic understanding of the new imperialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMarxian school of sociology. 0aNation-state and globalization. 0aState, ThexPhilosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Marxism. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Sociology. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846181640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438461816423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438461816/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles